## APPENDIX A

A Proof OF (32)
This appendix section derives the channel reciprocity, i.e., the relationship between the uplink channel and the downlink channel. First, we can express these two cascaded channels as

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \mathbf{H}_{\mathrm{BI}} \bar{\Gamma} \mathbf{H}_{\mathrm{IU}}=\mathbf{A}_{\mathrm{B}}(\boldsymbol{\vartheta}) \boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{\mathrm{BI}} \mathbf{A}_{\mathrm{I}}^{\top}(\boldsymbol{\vartheta}) \bar{\Gamma} \mathbf{A}_{\mathrm{I}}(\boldsymbol{\phi}) \boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{\mathrm{IU}} \mathbf{A}_{\mathrm{U}}^{\top}(\boldsymbol{\varphi}), \\
& \mathbf{H}_{\mathrm{UI}} \bar{\Gamma} \mathbf{H}_{\mathrm{IB}}=\mathbf{A}_{\mathrm{U}}(\boldsymbol{\varphi}) \boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{\mathrm{IU}} \mathbf{A}_{\mathrm{I}}^{\top}(\boldsymbol{\phi}) \bar{\Gamma} \mathbf{A}_{\mathrm{I}}(\boldsymbol{\theta}) \boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{\mathrm{BI}} \mathbf{A}_{\mathrm{B}}^{\top}(\boldsymbol{\vartheta})
\end{aligned}
$$

where $\bar{\Gamma}=\left(\boldsymbol{\Gamma}^{-1}-\mathbf{S}\right)^{-1}$. According to (19), we have

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \operatorname{vec}\left(\mathbf{H}_{\mathrm{BI}} \bar{\Gamma} \mathbf{H}_{\mathrm{IU}}\right) \\
& =\left(\mathbf{A}_{\mathrm{U}}(\boldsymbol{\varphi}) \otimes \mathbf{A}_{\mathrm{B}}(\boldsymbol{\vartheta})\right)\left(\boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{\mathrm{IU}} \otimes \boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{\mathrm{BI}}\right)\left(\mathbf{A}_{\mathrm{I}}^{\top}(\boldsymbol{\phi}) \otimes \mathbf{A}_{\mathrm{I}}^{\top}(\boldsymbol{\theta})\right) \boldsymbol{\xi} \\
& =\left(\underbrace{\left(\mathbf{A}_{\mathrm{U}}(\boldsymbol{\varphi}) \boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{\mathrm{IU}} \mathbf{A}_{\mathrm{I}}^{\top}(\boldsymbol{\phi})\right) \otimes\left(\mathbf{A}_{\mathrm{B}}(\boldsymbol{\vartheta}) \boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{\mathrm{BI}} \mathbf{A}_{\mathrm{I}}^{\top}(\boldsymbol{\theta})\right)}_{\mathbf{G}_{\mathrm{mc}}^{\mathrm{UL}} \in \mathbb{C}^{\mathcal{N}_{\mathrm{U}} \mathcal{N}_{\mathrm{B}} \times \mathcal{N}_{\mathrm{I}}^{\mathrm{T}}}}\right) \boldsymbol{\xi}
\end{aligned}
$$

where $\boldsymbol{\xi}=\operatorname{vec}(\bar{\Gamma})$. Similarly, we can express the downlink channel as

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \operatorname{vec}\left(\mathbf{H}_{\mathrm{UI}} \bar{\Gamma} \mathbf{H}_{\mathrm{IB}}\right) \\
& =\left(\mathbf{A}_{\mathrm{B}}(\boldsymbol{\vartheta}) \otimes \mathbf{A}_{\mathrm{U}}(\boldsymbol{\varphi})\right)\left(\boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{\mathrm{BI}} \otimes \boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{\mathrm{IU}}\right)\left(\mathbf{A}_{\mathrm{I}}^{\top}(\boldsymbol{\theta}) \otimes \mathbf{A}_{\mathrm{I}}^{\top}(\boldsymbol{\phi})\right) \boldsymbol{\xi} \\
& =\left(\underbrace{\left(\mathbf{A}_{\mathrm{B}}(\vartheta) \boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{\mathrm{BI}} \mathbf{A}_{\mathrm{I}}^{\top}(\boldsymbol{\theta})\right) \otimes\left(\mathbf{A}_{\mathrm{U}}(\boldsymbol{\varphi}) \boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{\mathrm{IU}} \mathbf{A}_{\mathrm{I}}^{\top}(\boldsymbol{\phi})\right)}_{\mathbf{G}_{\mathrm{mc}}^{\mathrm{UL}} \in \mathbb{C}^{\mathcal{N}_{\mathrm{U}} \mathcal{N}_{\mathrm{B}} \times \mathcal{N}_{\mathrm{I}}^{\mathrm{T}}}}\right) \boldsymbol{\xi}
\end{aligned}
$$

By comparing (A.3) and (A.4), it can be observed that the uplink and downlink equivalent channels, $\mathbf{G}_{\mathrm{mc}}^{\mathrm{UL}}$ and $\mathbf{G}_{\mathrm{mc}}^{\mathrm{DL}}$, contain the same entries but are arranged in different layouts. Therefore, $\mathbf{G}_{\mathrm{mc}}^{\mathrm{DL}}$ can be derived directly from $\mathbf{G}_{\mathrm{mc}}^{\mathrm{UL}}$, and (A.4) yields (32).

## APPENDIX C
## Proof of Proposition 1

Both functions, $f(\gamma)$ and $g\left(\gamma \mid \gamma_{i}\right)$, are a mapping: $\mathbb{C}^{N_{1}} \rightarrow$ $\mathbb{R}$. Following the complex-value differentiation theory in [57], [60], we rewrite the two functions $f(\gamma)$ and $g\left(\gamma \mid \gamma_{i}\right)$ as $f\left(\gamma, \gamma^{*}\right)$ and $g\left(\gamma, \gamma^{*} \mid \gamma_{i}\right)$, respectively. Here, $\gamma$ and $\gamma^{*}$ are treated as two linearly independent variables.

According to (40) and (42), we have

$$
\begin{aligned}
& g\left(\gamma, \gamma^{*} \mid \gamma_{i}\right)=-\gamma^{\mathrm{H}} \mathbf{Q}_{i} \gamma+K\left(\gamma-\gamma_{i}\right)^{\mathrm{H}}\left(\gamma-\gamma_{i}\right)-\gamma_{i}^{\mathrm{H}} \mathbf{q} \gamma^{\mathrm{T}} \mathbf{B} \gamma_{i} \\
& -\gamma_{i}^{\mathrm{H}} \mathbf{B}^{\mathrm{H}} \gamma^{*} \mathbf{q}^{\mathrm{H}} \gamma_{i}-\gamma_{i}^{\mathrm{H}} \mathbf{B}^{\mathrm{H}} \gamma^{*} \gamma_{i}^{\mathrm{T}} \mathbf{B} \gamma_{i}-\gamma_{i}^{\mathrm{H}} \mathbf{B}^{\mathrm{H}} \gamma_{i}^{*} \gamma^{\mathrm{T}} \mathbf{B} \gamma_{i}
\end{aligned}
$$

We can then observe that

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \frac{\partial^{2} g\left(\gamma, \gamma^{*} \mid \gamma_{i}\right)}{\partial \gamma \partial \gamma}=\frac{\partial^{2} g\left(\gamma, \gamma^{*} \mid \gamma_{i}\right)}{\partial \gamma^{*} \partial \gamma^{*}}=\mathbf{0} \\
& \frac{\partial^{2} g\left(\gamma, \gamma^{*} \mid \gamma_{i}\right)}{\partial \gamma \partial \gamma^{*}}=\left(\frac{\partial^{2} g\left(\gamma, \gamma^{*} \mid \gamma_{i}\right)}{\partial \gamma^{*} \partial \gamma}\right)^{\mathrm{T}}=K \mathbf{I}-\mathbf{Q}_{i}
\end{aligned}
$$

Thus, the full complex Hessian matrix of $g\left(\gamma, \gamma^{*} \mid \gamma_{i}\right)$ is given by [61]

$$
\mathbf{H}_{\gamma, \gamma^{*}}^{i}=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
\left(K \mathbf{I}-\mathbf{Q}_{i}\right)^{\mathrm{T}} & \mathbf{0} \\
\mathbf{0} & K \mathbf{I}-\mathbf{Q}_{i}
\end{array}\right] \succeq \mathbf{0}
$$

Here, the positive semi-definiteness of $\mathbf{H}_{\gamma, \gamma^{*}}^{i}$ is ensured by (41). Then, according to the second-order condition of convex functions [55, Sec. 3.1.4], $g\left(\gamma, \gamma^{*} \mid \gamma_{i}\right)$ is convex. Hence, Condition 1 in Appendix B is satisfied.

Next, we derive the first-order derivatives of $f\left(\gamma, \gamma^{*}\right)$ and $g\left(\gamma, \gamma^{*} \mid \gamma_{i}\right)$ to assess whether they satisfy Condition 2. Based on (40), we can derive:

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \frac{\partial f\left(\gamma, \gamma^{*}\right)}{\partial \gamma}=-\left(\gamma^{\mathrm{H}} \mathbf{q}\right) \mathbf{q}^{*}-\left(\gamma^{\mathrm{H}} \mathbf{q}\right)\left(\mathbf{B}+\mathbf{B}^{\mathrm{T}}\right) \gamma-\left(\gamma^{\mathrm{H}} \mathbf{B}^{\mathrm{H}} \gamma^{*}\right) \mathbf{q}^{*} \\
& -\left(\gamma^{\mathrm{H}} \mathbf{B}^{\mathrm{H}} \gamma^{*}\right)\left(\mathbf{B}+\mathbf{B}^{\mathrm{T}}\right) \gamma \\
& \frac{\partial f\left(\gamma, \gamma^{*}\right)}{\partial \gamma^{*}}=-\left(\gamma^{\mathrm{T}} \mathbf{q}^{*}\right) \mathbf{q}-\left(\gamma^{\mathrm{T}} \mathbf{q}^{*}\right)\left(\mathbf{B}^{\mathrm{H}}+\mathbf{B}^{*}\right) \gamma^{*}-\left(\gamma^{\mathrm{T}} \mathbf{B} \gamma\right) \mathbf{q} \\
& -\left(\gamma^{\mathrm{T}} \mathbf{B} \gamma\right)\left(\mathbf{B}^{\mathrm{H}}+\mathbf{B}^{*}\right) \gamma^{*} \\
& \frac{\partial g\left(\gamma, \gamma^{*} \mid \gamma_{i}\right)}{\partial \gamma}=-\left(\gamma^{\mathrm{H}} \mathbf{q}\right) \mathbf{q}^{*}-\left(\gamma^{\mathrm{H}} \mathbf{q}\right) \mathbf{B}^{\mathrm{T}} \gamma_{i}-\left(\gamma^{\mathrm{H}} \mathbf{B}^{\mathrm{H}} \gamma_{i}^{*}\right) \mathbf{q}^{*} \\
& -\left(\gamma^{\mathrm{H}} \mathbf{B}^{\mathrm{H}} \gamma_{i}^{*}\right) \mathbf{B}^{\mathrm{T}} \gamma_{i}+K\left(\gamma^{*}-\gamma_{i}^{*}\right)-\left(\gamma_{i}^{\mathrm{H}} \mathbf{q}\right) \mathbf{B} \gamma_{i}-\left(\gamma_{i}^{\mathrm{H}} \mathbf{B}^{\mathrm{H}} \gamma_{i}^{*}\right) \mathbf{B} \gamma_{i} \\
& \frac{\partial g\left(\gamma, \gamma^{*} \mid \gamma_{i}\right)}{\partial \gamma^{*}}=-\left(\gamma^{\mathrm{T}} \mathbf{q}^{*}\right) \mathbf{q}-\left(\gamma^{\mathrm{T}} \mathbf{q}^{*}\right) \mathbf{B}^{\mathrm{H}} \gamma_{i}-\left(\gamma_{i}^{\mathrm{T}} \mathbf{B} \gamma\right) \mathbf{q} \\
& -\left(\gamma_{i}^{\mathrm{T}} \mathbf{B} \gamma\right) \mathbf{B}^{\mathrm{H}} \gamma_{i}^{*}+K\left(\gamma-\gamma_{i}\right)-\left(\gamma_{i}^{\mathrm{T}} \mathbf{q}^{*}\right) \mathbf{B}^{*} \gamma_{i}^{*}-\left(\gamma_{i}^{\mathrm{T}} \mathbf{B} \gamma_{i}\right) \mathbf{B}^{*} \gamma_{i}^{*}
\end{aligned}
$$

By comparing (C.5) and (C.7), we can see that $\frac{\partial f\left(\gamma, \gamma^{*}\right)}{\partial \gamma}\left\lvert\, \gamma=\gamma_{i}=\frac{\partial g\left(\gamma, \gamma^{*} \mid \gamma_{i}\right)}{\partial \gamma}\right.$ $\left.\left.\right|_{\gamma=\gamma_{i}}$. By comparing (C.6) and (C.8), we can see that $\frac{\partial f\left(\gamma, \gamma^{*}\right)}{\partial \gamma^{*}}\left.\right|_{\gamma=\gamma_{i}}=\frac{\partial g\left(\gamma, \gamma^{*} \mid \gamma_{i}\right)}{\partial \gamma^{*}}\right|_{\gamma=\gamma_{i}}$. Thus Condition 2 in Appendix B is satisfied, which concludes the proof.
